				posted 2005-01-14 00:42&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;
				<A href="edit.php?board=player&id=15310"><IMG alt="Edit/Delete Message" src="http://www.archspace.org/image/forum/edit.gif" border=0></A> 
			    <A href="reply.php?board=player&id=15248"><IMG alt="Reply w/Quote" src="http://www.archspace.org/image/forum/quote.gif" border=0></A>
			    <HR color=#000000 SIZE=-1>
			  	organising 2, 20 or 2 million ships isnt a real problem. you can do it in a lot of different ways...the cheapest (in terms of CPU) is planetarions way of doing it ...group 2 million ships simply by bunching them together with a linear number. i.e. <br />
frigate 24,000,000<br />
destroyer 10,000,000<br />
A better way (IMHO - feel free to disagree) would be to set position by type in an applet -- drag and drop a shape representing a ship multiple times <br />
i.e.     DE<br />
      DE BS DE<br />
         DE<br />
and then allocate a number representing the ships and a weighting ... so for 8 million destroyers with 1 million battleships :<br />
      DE (4 mil)<br />
  DE(2mil) BS(1 mil) DE (1 mil)<br />
         DE (1 mil)<br />
of course, the interface will have to be refined when implemented, but the basic concept is simple.<br />
This should take care of the rings/defense in depth problem..of course the mathematics of doing it in real time while calculating damage with different weapons are pretty complex ...but doable i think.<br />
the tougher challenge is line of sight visibility and battlespace illumination with doppler shift due to speeds of superluminal targets...im still thinking about that one. to develop an accurate model you must calculate weapon speed, target speed, attacker line of sight (i.e. a wall of 4 million DEs will hide a lot of space from sheer physical size alone), weapon line of sight once launched, attacker speed etc. its doable but doing it on a server in real time without melting the cpu is a real challenge. the watershed algorithm takes a while for even a 512 x 512 2D grid when calculating line of sight and illumination.<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
			   <P align=right></P>
			</TD>
